style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">St. Louis, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">July&#160;23, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  Enterprise Financial Services Corp (NASDAQ: EFSC) (the &#8220;Company&#8221;) reported net income of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$8.7 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, a decrease of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.6 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">7%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, as compared to the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter.  Net income per diluted share was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.43</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, a decrease of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">7%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.46</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;per diluted share for the linked first quarter due to lower contractual interest on Purchase credit impaired ("PCI") loans and a decrease in reversal of provision for loan loss.  </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;net income was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">22%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;higher than the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$7.2 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;reported in the prior year period, and diluted earnings per share were </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">19%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;higher than the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.36</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;reported a year ago.  The increase in net income over the prior year was primarily due to an increase in net interest income from strong loan growth, a decrease in noninterest expenses from improved expense control initiatives, and a decline in provision reversal for PCI loans.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">On a core basis</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:7pt">1</sup></font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, the Company reported net income of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$7.7 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.38</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;per diluted share, for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$7.1 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.35</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;per diluted share, in the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter. &#160;The increase was due to an increase in net interest income from strong loan growth and increases in noninterest income.  </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;core net income increased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">23%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$6.3 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the prior year period, and diluted core earnings per share grew </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">23%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.31</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the prior year period.  The increase was primarily due to increases in earning asset balances driving growth in core net interest income combined with a reduction in noninterest expenses.  </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company's Board approved an additional one cent per common share increase in the Company&#8217;s quarterly dividend to $0.07 per common share from $0.06 for the third quarter of 2015, payable on September 30, 2015 to shareholders of record as of September 15, 2015.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:13px;text-align:left;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Peter Benoist, President and CEO, commented, &#8220;Enterprise reported another solid quarter, with EPS up 19% over the prior year period and second quarter Return on average assets again exceeding one percent.&#8221;</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:13px;text-align:left;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">"On a core operating basis, results were strong across the board,&#8221; said Benoist. &#8220;Core EPS increased 23% over last year&#8217;s second quarter, driven by robust loan growth, stable margins and lower expenses.  Loan growth was a particular highlight, with core loans increasing at an 18% annual rate.  Year to date, core loans outstanding have increased 4%, or 9% annualized."</font></div><br><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:9pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:6pt">1 </sup></font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;">A non-GAAP measure.  Refer to discussion &amp; reconciliation of these measures in the accompanying financial tables.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:center;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">1</font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><a name="sDDEC2DA65BF44508ED5C4E49E0F5AF13"></a><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:13px;text-align:left;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Benoist added, &#8220;We continued to successfully defend our core net interest margin, which held firm in the second quarter.  Our current core net interest margin is five basis points higher than a year ago.  Expenses remain well controlled within our forecasted range and, through the first half of the year, we&#8217;ve pushed our efficiency ratio down below 60%.&#8221;</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;">Net Interest Income</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Net interest income in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter increased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.2 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;from the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.5 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;from the prior year period due to lower interest expense from the payoff of higher cost debt in the prior year and an increase in portfolio loan balances.  The net interest margin on a fully tax equivalent basis was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">3.85%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter, compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">3.92%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter, and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">4.04%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">. </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">In the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, the yield on PCI loans was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">18.33%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, as compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">20.85%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in the linked quarter and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">20.84%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in the prior year period.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The cost of interest-bearing deposits declined </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">two</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">0.52%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;from the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter, and was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">six</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points lower than the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of 2014, primarily from lower rates on time deposit balances.  The cost of interest-bearing liabilities declined </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">two</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points as compared to the linked quarter to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">0.54%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">11</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points from the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  The improvement was primarily due to the prepayment of $50 million of FHLB borrowings in December 2014 and the aforementioned improvement in deposit costs.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Core net interest income</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:7pt">1</sup></font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;increased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">9%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;compared to the prior year period due to strong portfolio loan growth and managed decreases in the cost of interest-bearing liabilities as discussed above.  Core net interest income increased by </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.7 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$26.3 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;when compared to the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter, and core net interest margin remained stable at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">3.46%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Core net interest margin</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:7pt">1</sup></font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;increased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">five</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points from the prior year quarter primarily due to the effect of the FHLB debt prepayment in December 2014 and loan growth improving our earning asset mix.  These factors mitigated continued pressure on portfolio loan yields and reductions in PCI loan balances, as those balances continue to run-off.  Pressure on loan yields and continued reductions in PCI loan balances could lead to a modest decline in core net interest margin in the second half of 2015.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;">Portfolio loans</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Portfolio loans grew to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$2.5 billion</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, increasing </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$107 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">18%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;on an annualized basis, when compared to the linked quarter.  On a year over year basis, portfolio loans increased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$291 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">13%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  The Company continues to expect loan growth at or above </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">10%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for 2015.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Commercial and industrial ("C&amp;I") loans increased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$69.9 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;during the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;compared to the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter.  C&amp;I loans represented </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">53%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;of the Company's loan portfolio at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, relatively consistent with </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">March&#160;31, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  C&amp;I loans grew </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$200 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">18%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, since </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  During the 12 months ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, the Company also grew loans in all other major categories.</font></div><br><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:9pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:6pt">1 </sup></font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;">A non-GAAP measure.  Refer to discussion &amp; reconciliation of these measures in the accompanying financial tables.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:center;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">2</font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><a name="sDDEC2DA65BF44508ED5C4E49E0F5AF13"></a><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company continues to focus on originating high-quality C&amp;I relationships, as they typically have variable interest rates and allow for cross selling opportunities involving other banking products.  Our specialized market segments, particularly enterprise value lending and life insurance premium finance, have contributed to the growth in the C&amp;I category.  C&amp;I loan growth also supports our efforts to maintain the Company's asset sensitive interest rate risk position.  At </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">62%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;of our portfolio loans had variable interest rates.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;">PCI loans and other real estate covered under FDIC loss share agreements</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">PCI loans totaled </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$88 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, a decrease of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$7.1 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">8%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, from the linked </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter, and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$30.9 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, or </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">26%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, from the prior year period, primarily as a result of principal paydowns and accelerated loan payoffs.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:13px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Other real estate covered under FDIC loss share agreements at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$7.9 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, a </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">122%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;increase from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$3.6 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">March&#160;31, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  The significant increase was mainly due to foreclosure on a property from one relationship.  During the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, the Company sold </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$0.7 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;of other real estate, resulting in a negligible net gain.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company remeasures contractual and expected cash flows on PCI loans on a periodic basis.  When the remeasurement process results in a decrease in expected cash flows due to an increase in expected credit losses, impairment is recorded through the provision for loan losses.  Similarly, when expected credit losses decrease in the remeasurement process, prior recorded impairment is reversed before the yield is increased prospectively.  Concurrently, the FDIC loss share receivable is adjusted to reflect anticipated future cash to be received from the FDIC.  In the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">no</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;provision or reversal of provision for loan losses was recorded for any loan pools.  Any provision or provision benefit would be partially offset through noninterest income by a change in the FDIC loss share receivable.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:13px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Actual cash collections in excess of expected cash flows that represent accelerated loan payoffs result in the recognition of income, but also generally result in a decrease in the FDIC loss share receivable. These cash flows are, by their nature, unpredictable and can vary significantly period to period.  Actual cash collections in excess of expected cash flows from loan payoffs and real estate sales in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter resulted in accelerated discount income of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$1.3 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">, which was partially offset by a decrease in the FDIC loss share receivable.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:13px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The following table illustrates the financial contribution of PCI loans and other real estate covered under FDIC loss share agreements for the most recent five quarters:   </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:center;font-size:10pt;"><div The positive trends in deposits reflect enhanced deposit gathering efforts in both commercial and business banking.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Noninterest-bearing deposits decreased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$22.7 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">March&#160;31, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;and decreased </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">$17.0 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;compared to the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">. Capital ratios for the current quarter are&#160;based on the Company&#8217;s interpretations of the Basel III regulatory capital framework as applied to the Company&#8217;s current businesses and operations and are subject to, among other things, completion and filing of the Company&#8217;s regulatory reports and ongoing regulatory review and implementation guidance.  The attached tables contain a reconciliation of these ratios to U.S. GAAP financial measures.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company's effective tax rate was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">35.3%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">35.0%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">March&#160;31, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">33.9%</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">June&#160;30, 2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.</font></div><br><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:9pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:6pt">1 </sup></font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;">A non-GAAP measure.  Refer to discussion &amp; reconciliation of these measures in the accompanying financial tables.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:center;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">5</font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><a name="sDDEC2DA65BF44508ED5C4E49E0F5AF13"></a><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;">Use of Non-GAAP Financial Measures</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;"><sup style="vertical-align:top;line-height:120%;font-size:7pt">1</sup>&#160;</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company's accounting and reporting policies conform to generally accepted accounting principles in the United States (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;) and the prevailing practices in the banking industry. However, the Company provides other financial measures, such as Core net income margin and other Core performance measures, tangible common equity ratio and Common equity tier 1 capital ratio, in this release that are considered &#8220;non-GAAP financial measures.&#8221; Generally, a non-GAAP financial measure is a numerical measure of a company's financial performance, financial position or cash flows that exclude (or include) amounts that are included in (or excluded from) the most directly comparable measure calculated and presented in accordance with GAAP.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company considers its Core performance measures presented in this earnings release and the included tables as important measures of financial performance, even though they are non-GAAP measures, as they provide supplemental information by which to evaluate the impact of PCI loans and related income and expenses, the impact of nonrecurring items, and the Company's operating performance on an ongoing basis.  Core performance measures include contractual interest on PCI loans but exclude incremental accretion on these loans.  Core performance measures also exclude the Change in FDIC receivable, Gain or loss of other real estate covered under FDIC loss share agreements and expenses directly related to the PCI loans and other assets covered under FDIC loss share agreements.  Core performance measures also exclude certain other income and expense items the Company believes to be not indicative of or useful to measure the Company's operating performance on an ongoing basis.  The attached tables contain a reconciliation of these Core performance measures to the GAAP measures.  The Company believes that the tangible common equity and the Common equity tier 1 capital ratios provide useful information to investors about  the Company's capital strength even though they are considered to be non-GAAP financial measures and are not part of the regulatory capital requirements to which the Company is subject.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company believes these non-GAAP measures and ratios, when taken together with the corresponding GAAP measures and ratios, provide meaningful supplemental information regarding the Company's performance and capital strength. The Company's management uses, and believes that investors benefit from referring to, these non-GAAP measures and ratios in assessing the Company's operating results and related trends and when forecasting future periods. However, these non-GAAP measures and ratios should be considered in addition to, and not as a substitute for or preferable to, ratios prepared in accordance with GAAP.  In the tables below, the Company has provided a reconciliation of, where applicable, the most comparable GAAP financial measures and ratios to the non-GAAP financial measures and ratios, or a reconciliation of the non-GAAP calculation of the financial measure for the periods indicated.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">The Company will host a conference call and webcast at 2:30 p.m. Central time on Thursday, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">July&#160;23, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">.  During the call, management will review the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;results and related matters.  This press release as well as a related slide presentation will be accessible on Enterprise Financial Services Corp's website at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;color:#0000ff;text-decoration:underline;">www.enterprisebank.com</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#32;under &#8220;Investor Relations&#8221; beginning prior to the scheduled broadcast of the conference call.  The call can be accessed via this same website page, or via telephone at 1-877-876-9176 (Conference ID #7827106.)  A recorded replay of the conference call will be available on the website beginning two hours after the call's completion.  The telephone replay will be available at 1-888-203-1112 (replay passcode #7827106.)  The replays will be available for approximately two weeks following the conference call. </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">Enterprise Financial Services Corp operates commercial banking and wealth management businesses in metropolitan St. Louis, Kansas City, and Phoenix. <DIV><FONT size="1" style="font-size:1pt;color:white">17   USE OF NON-GAAP FINANCIAL MEASURES    The Company&#39;s accounting and reporting policies conform to generally accepted accounting principles in the United States   (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;) and the prevailing practices in the banking industry. However, the Company provides other financial measures, such as   Core net income margin and other Core performance measures, in this presentation that are considered &#8220;non-GAAP financial   measures.&#8221; Generally, a non-GAAP financial measure is a numerical measure of a company&#39;s financial performance, financial   position or cash flows that exclude (or include) amounts that are included in (or excluded from) the most directly comparable   measure calculated and presented in accordance with GAAP.      The Company considers its Core performance measures presented in presentation as important measures of financial   performance, even though they are non-GAAP measures, as they provide supplemental information by which to evaluate the   impact of PCI loans and related income and expenses, the impact of nonrecurring items, and the Company&#39;s operating   performance on an ongoing basis.  Core performance measures include contractual interest on PCI loans but exclude   incremental accretion on these loans.  Core performance measures also exclude the Change in FDIC receivable, Gain or loss of   other real estate covered under FDIC loss share agreements and expenses directly related to the PCI loans and other assets   covered under FDIC loss share agreements.  Core performance measures also exclude certain other income and expense items   the Company believes to be not indicative of or useful to measure the Company&#39;s operating performance on an ongoing basis.    The attached tables contain a reconciliation of these Core performance measures to the GAAP measures.       The Company believes these non-GAAP measures and ratios, when taken together with the corresponding GAAP measures and   ratios, provide meaningful supplemental information regarding the Company&#39;s performance and capital strength. The Company&#39;s   management uses, and believes that investors benefit from referring to, these non-GAAP measures and ratios in assessing the   Company&#39;s operating results and related trends and when forecasting future periods. However, these non-GAAP measures and   ratios should be considered in addition to, and not as a substitute for or preferable to, ratios prepared in accordance with GAAP.    In the tables below, the Company has provided a reconciliation of, where applicable, the most comparable GAAP financial   measures and ratios to the non-GAAP financial measures and ratios, or a reconciliation of the non-GAAP calculation of the   financial measure for the periods indicated.      Peer group data consists of banks with total assets from $1-$10 billion with commercial loans greater than 20% and consumer   loans less than 20%.        </FONT></DIV>
<P><HR noshade><P>
